<section id="fundamentals">
  <h2>Networking Fundamentals</h2>

  <div class="card">
    <p>
      A <span class="highlight">computer network</span> is a group of connected devices that communicate
      and share information with each other. Networks allow devices to share files, printers, internet access,
      and other resources.
    </p>

    <h3>Types of Networks</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>LAN (Local Area Network):</strong> A network covering a small area like a classroom, house, or office.</li>
      <li><strong>WAN (Wide Area Network):</strong> A network that spans large geographic areas. The internet is the biggest WAN.</li>
      <li><strong>WLAN (Wireless Local Area Network):</strong> A wireless version of a LAN using Wi-Fi.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <div class="grid">
    <div class="card">
      <h3>Network Devices</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Router:</strong> Connects networks together and directs traffic.</li>
        <li><strong>Switch:</strong> Connects devices inside the same network.</li>
        <li><strong>Access Point:</strong> Provides wireless access to devices.</li>
        <li><strong>Client:</strong> A device requesting services from another device.</li>
        <li><strong>Server:</strong> A computer that provides services or resources.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <h3>Networking Vocabulary</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Bandwidth:</strong> The amount of data transferred over a network.</li>
        <li><strong>Protocol:</strong> Rules that devices use to communicate.</li>
        <li><strong>Packet:</strong> A small unit of data sent across a network.</li>
        <li><strong>IP Address:</strong> A logical address assigned to a device.</li>
        <li><strong>MAC Address:</strong> A physical hardware address assigned to a network card.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

