<section id="ipmac">
  <h2>IP Addressing and MAC Addresses</h2>

  <div class="card">
    <h3>What is an IP Address?</h3>
    <p>
      An IP address is a unique address assigned to a device on a network. It helps devices locate and communicate with each other.
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>IPv4:</strong> Uses 32 bits and appears as four numbers separated by periods. Example: 192.168.1.1</li>
      <li><strong>IPv6:</strong> Uses 128 bits and was created to provide more addresses for modern devices.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <div class="card">
    <h3>Private and Public IP Addresses</h3>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Private IP Example:</strong> 192.168.0.15</li>
      <li><strong>Public IP Example:</strong> 8.8.8.8</li>
      <li><strong>Subnet Mask:</strong> Helps identify the network and host portions of an IP address.</li>
      <li><strong>Default Gateway:</strong> The router used to access outside networks.</li>
      <li><strong>DNS Server:</strong> Translates website names into IP addresses.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <div class="card">
    <h3>What is a MAC Address?</h3>

    <p>
      A MAC address is a hardware address permanently assigned to a network interface card.
      The first three octets identify the manufacturer. This section is called the
      <strong>OUI (Organizationally Unique Identifier)</strong>.
    </p>

    <p>
      Example MAC Address:<br>
      00:1A:2B:4C:5D:6E
    </p>

    <p>
      In this example, <strong>00:1A:2B</strong> identifies the manufacturer.
    </p>
  </div>

